# {{.ProjectName}}

Production-ready Go backend with clean architecture, REST + gRPC support, and PostgreSQL persistence.

## Features

- ✅ Clean 4-layer architecture (domain, application, ports, adapters)
- ✅ **Dual Protocol**: REST (via grpc-gateway) + gRPC APIs
- ✅ **PostgreSQL** with pgx driver and sqlc for type-safe queries
- ✅ **buf** for proto management and code generation
- ✅ **Database migrations** with golang-migrate
{{- if .Features.Auth}}
- ✅ JWT authentication + OAuth2
{{- end}}
{{- if .Features.Observability}}
- ✅ Full observability (Prometheus + OpenTelemetry + structured logging)
{{- end}}
{{- if .Features.Docker}}
- ✅ Docker environment with docker-compose
{{- end}}

## Quick Start

### Prerequisites

- Go 1.22+
- [buf CLI](https://buf.build) for proto generation
- [sqlc](https://sqlc.dev) for SQL code generation
- [golang-migrate](https://github.com/golang-migrate/migrate) for database migrations
{{- if .Features.Docker}}
- Docker + Docker Compose
{{- end}}

### Setup

```bash
# Install dependencies
go mod download

{{- if .Features.Docker}}
# Start services (PostgreSQL{{if .Features.Auth}}, Redis{{end}}{{if .Features.Observability}}, Prometheus, Grafana{{end}})
docker-compose up -d
{{- else}}
# Ensure PostgreSQL is running on localhost:5432
{{- end}}

# Generate code from proto files
make proto

# Generate Go code from SQL queries
make sqlc

# Run database migrations
make migrate-up

# Run the server
make run
```

### Endpoints

- **REST API**: `http://localhost:8080/api/v1/`
- **gRPC API**: `localhost:9090`
- **Health Check**:
  - REST: `http://localhost:8080/api/v1/health`
  - gRPC: `grpcurl -plaintext localhost:9090 api.v1.HealthService/Check`
{{- if .Features.Observability}}
- **Metrics**: `http://localhost:8080/metrics`
{{- end}}

## Project Structure

```
.
├── cmd/
│   └── server/          # Application entry point (HTTP + gRPC servers)
├── internal/
│   ├── domain/          # Business entities
│   ├── application/     # Use cases
│   ├── ports/           # Interface adapters
│   │   ├── http/        # REST endpoints (grpc-gateway)
│   │   └── grpc/        # gRPC service implementations
│   ├── adapters/        # External integrations
│   │   └── postgres/    # Database adapter (pgx + sqlc)
│   ├── config/          # Configuration management
│   └── gen/             # Generated proto code (auto-generated)
├── api/
│   ├── proto/v1/        # Protocol buffer definitions
│   ├── buf.yaml         # buf configuration
│   └── buf.gen.yaml     # Code generation config
├── migrations/          # SQL migration files
├── scripts/             # Helper scripts
├── pkg/                 # Shared packages
└── tests/               # Integration and E2E tests
```

## Development

### Generate Code

```bash
# Generate Go code from proto files
make proto

# Generate Go code from SQL queries
make sqlc
```

### Database Migrations

```bash
# Apply migrations
make migrate-up

# Rollback last migration
make migrate-down

# Check migration version
make migrate-version
```

### Testing

```bash
# Run all tests
make test

# Run integration tests
make test-integration

# Run with coverage
go test -cover ./...
```

### Linting

```bash
make lint
```

### Building

```bash
# Build binary
make build

# Run binary
./bin/server
```

## Configuration

Configuration is managed via Viper with YAML files and environment variable overrides.

**Config file**: `configs/config.dev.yaml` (development) or `configs/config.prod.yaml` (production)

**Environment variables** (prefix with `APP_`):
```bash
export APP_SERVER_PORT=8080
export APP_DATABASE_HOST=localhost
export APP_DATABASE_PORT=5432
export APP_DATABASE_NAME={{.ProjectName}}_dev
export APP_DATABASE_USER=postgres
export APP_DATABASE_PASSWORD=postgres
```

## gRPC API

The gRPC API is automatically exposed as REST via grpc-gateway. All proto definitions are in `api/proto/v1/`.

### Testing gRPC Endpoints

**Using grpcurl**:
```bash
# List services
grpcurl -plaintext localhost:9090 list

# Call health check
grpcurl -plaintext localhost:9090 api.v1.HealthService/Check

# Call ready check
grpcurl -plaintext localhost:9090 api.v1.HealthService/Ready
```

**Using REST (grpc-gateway)**:
```bash
curl http://localhost:8080/api/v1/health
curl http://localhost:8080/api/v1/ready
```

